Understanding Operating Systems (OS)

An Operating System (OS) is the main software that manages all hardware and software on a computer. It acts as a bridge between the user and the
computer hardware ‚Äî controlling how applications use system resources like CPU, memory, and storage.

üíª Types of Operating Systems
1. Client Operating System

Installed on personal devices like laptops, desktops, or smartphones.
Designed for individual users.
Examples: Windows 11, macOS, Ubuntu Desktop, Android
Main focus: User interface, applications, and ease of use.

2. Server Operating System

Installed on powerful machines (servers) to provide services to multiple clients or users over a network.
Designed for performance, security, and reliability.
Examples: Windows Server, Ubuntu Server, Red Hat Enterprise Linux, CentOS
Main focus: Managing multiple users, handling databases, web hosting, file sharing.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

How Linux Came Into Existence

In 1991, a student named Linus Torvalds from Finland wanted a free and open-source alternative to UNIX.
He created a small OS kernel and shared it online for collaboration.
Developers around the world contributed, and this project became known as Linux.
So, LINUS (person) ‚Üí created LINUX (OS).

Linus Torvalds (Student, 1991)
           ‚Üì
Wanted free UNIX-like system
           ‚Üì
Created Kernel (core of OS)
           ‚Üì
Shared Online (Open Source)
           ‚Üì
Community Contributions
           ‚Üì
  LINUX Operating System


Why Linux Became Popular:

Free & Open Source
Secure and Stable
Runs on everything ‚Äî from servers to Android phones.

