‚öôÔ∏è Explanation (in few lines)

The Kernel is the core part of an operating system.
It connects user applications to the hardware.
It controls everything ‚Äî CPU scheduling, memory allocation, file access, and device communication.
You can think of it as the ‚Äúengine‚Äù of your OS ‚Äî hidden but always running.

üåç Real-world Use

In Android phones, the Linux kernel manages apps, memory, and hardware (camera, Wi-Fi, battery).
In servers, the kernel ensures smooth multitasking and security.
In computers, it helps multiple programs run efficiently without crashing.





